AWS RDS ‚Äì Notes
1Ô∏è‚É£ RDS

Amazon RDS is a managed relational database service in AWS.
It helps users create, operate, and scale databases without managing servers.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Supported Database Engines

RDS supports MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB, Oracle, SQL Server, and Amazon Aurora.
You can choose the engine based on application needs.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Managed Service

AWS handles patching, backups, monitoring, and maintenance.
This reduces administrative overhead for users.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Storage

RDS provides different storage types like General Purpose (SSD), Provisioned IOPS, and Magnetic.
Storage can be scaled as the database grows.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Backups

RDS automatically performs daily backups and transaction log backups.
Point-in-time recovery is supported.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Multi-AZ Deployment

Multi-AZ creates a standby database in another Availability Zone.
It improves availability and provides automatic failover.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Read Replicas

Read replicas are used to improve read performance.
They help reduce load on the primary database.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Security

RDS supports encryption at rest and in transit.
Access is controlled using IAM, security groups, and VPC.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Monitoring

RDS integrates with CloudWatch for monitoring metrics like CPU, memory, and storage.
Enhanced monitoring provides deeper insights.

üîü Use Cases

RDS is used for web applications, ERP systems, and transactional workloads.
It is ideal when a managed relational database is required.
